th minority languages, and recent Islamophobia. He also studies the introduction of multiculturalism into the lexicon and policy of the two countries and presents a nuanced analysis of how its meaning is understood differently on opposite sides of the border. An accessible and illuminating work, Building Nations from Diversity highlights the substantial differences between the US and Canada but ultimately concludes that they are more similar than most realize and are probably becoming more alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCultural pluralismzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzCanadaxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMulticulturalismzCanadaxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358320740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773583207423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773583207/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles